# Idea:
**For this problem, we simply need to prioritize the more valuable boxes first. To do this, we should sort the boxtypes array *(boxTypes)* in descending order by the number of units per box *(boxTypes[i] [1])*.**

**Then we can iterate through *boxTypes* and at each step, we should add as many of the boxes as we can, until we reach the truck size *(truckSize)*. We should add the number of boxes added multiplied by the units per box to our answer *(ans)*, and decrease *truckSize* by the same number of boxes**.

**Once the truck is full *(truckSize == 0)*, or once the iteration is done, we should return *ans*.**


**Time Complexity: O(N log N) where N is the length of boxTypes, for the sort
Space Complexity: O(1) to O(N) depending on the sort algorithm used**


```
class Solution {
    public int maximumUnits(int[][] boxTypes, int truckSize) {
     Arrays.sort(boxTypes, (a, b) -> b[1] - a[1]);
      int ans = 0;
      for(int[] b : boxTypes) {
        int count = Math.min(b[0], truckSize);
        ans += count * b[1];
        truckSize -= count;
        if(truckSize == 0) return ans;
      }
      return ans;
    }
}

