# Approach 1:
**The key point:** The more unit per box is, the more units can be added to truck. 
**Approach:** We can sort the box array by units per box from higher to lower. Hence, we will ge the higher units per box in the top of the array.

For test case: 2
initially: boxTypes = [[5,10],[2,5],[4,7],[3,9]]
after sorting: boxTypes = [[5,10],[3,9],[4,7],[2,5]]

Now, we will start picking box from *index-0*.

Pick index 0: [5,10] => spaceLeft = truckSize = 10 || currentBoxes = 5, unitsPerBox = 10, totalUnits = 5\*10 = 50, spaceLeft = 10-5 = 5
Pick index 1: [3,9] => spaceLeft = 5 || currentBoxes = 3, unitsPerBox = 9, totalUnits =50 + 3\*9 = 50 + 27 = 77, spaceLeft = 5-3 = 2
Pick index 2: [4,7] => spaceLeft = 2 || (cannot be picked all of the 4 boxes, have to pick as spaceLeft) 
currentBoxes = 4, unitsPerBox = 7, totalUnits =77 + 2\*7 = 77 + 14 = 91, spaceLeft = 2-2 = 0 
Pick index 3: [4,7] => spaceLeft = 0 || cannot be picked any further as no space left.
(no space left, terminate loop)

**Code:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    static bool sortByUnitPerItem(const vector<int>& v1, const vector<int>& v2) {
        return v1[1]>v2[1];
    }
    int maximumUnits(vector<vector<int>>& boxTypes, int truckSize) {
        sort(boxTypes.begin(), boxTypes.end(), sortByUnitPerItem);
        int currSpace=0, totalUnits=0;
        for(int i=0; i<boxTypes.size() && currSpace<truckSize; i++) {
            int currNumOfBox=boxTypes[i][0];
            int currUnitPerBox=boxTypes[i][1];
            if(currNumOfBox+currSpace>=truckSize) { //if all of the box can be picked
                int remainSpace = truckSize-currSpace;
                totalUnits += remainSpace * currUnitPerBox;
            } else {
                totalUnits += currNumOfBox * currUnitPerBox;
            }
            currSpace+=currNumOfBox;
        }
        return totalUnits;
    }
};
```
**Complexity:**
Time: O (n\*logn) [for sorting]
Space: O (1) [no extra space needed]
# Approach 2:
**The key point:** The max units per box is 1000, so, we can loop from 1000 to 1 (higher to lower boxPerUnit) without any sorting.
**Approach:** We can track units per box vs how many boxes of that kind and store them in the array.

For test case: 2
boxTypes = [[5,10],[2,5],[4,7],[3,9]]
array: (unitsPerBox = boxCount)
0 = 0
1 = 0
2 = 5
3 = 0
4 = 0
5 = 2
6 = 0
7 = 4
8 = 0
9 = 3
10 = 5
...all until 1000 = 0

Now, we can iterate from 1000 to 1 (higher to lower boxPerUnit).
....
for index 10 (5): spaceLeft = truckSize = 10 || currentBoxes = 5, unitsPerBox = 10, totalUnits = 5\*10 = 50, spaceLeft = 10-5 = 5
for index 9 (3): spaceLeft = 5 || currentBoxes = 3, unitsPerBox = 9, totalUnits =50 + 3\*9 = 50 + 27 = 77, spaceLeft = 5-3 = 2
for index 8 (0): spaceLeft = 2 || no boxes available for unitsPerBox = 8
...
for index 7 (4): spaceLeft = 2 || (cannot be picked all of the 4 boxes, have to pick as spaceLeft) 
currentBoxes = 4, unitsPerBox = 7, totalUnits =77 + 2\*7 = 77 + 14 = 91, spaceLeft = 2-2 = 0 
(no space left, terminate loop)

**Code:**
```
class Solution {
public:
    int maximumUnits(vector<vector<int>>& boxTypes, int truckSize) {
        int currSpaceLeft=truckSize, units=0;
        int arr[10001] = {0};
        for(int i=0; i<boxTypes.size(); i++) {
            arr[boxTypes[i][1]]+=boxTypes[i][0];
        }
        for(int i=1000; i>0; i--) {
            if(currSpaceLeft<=arr[i]) {
                units+=currSpaceLeft*i;
                break;
            } else {
                units+=arr[i]*i;
            }
            currSpaceLeft-=arr[i];
        }
        return units;
    }
};
```
