solutions.content:
Overall, it is the advanced verison of classic two sum problem. At first glance, it is easy to get a brutal force solution which will have LTE but I didn't try since the size of test cases would be 10^5. Therefore, the solution with time complexity O(n^2) would not be helpful for deriving an AC solution. **Note: constraints show 0 <= deliciousness[i] <= 2^20 and mean two 2 ^ 20 numbers may sum up to 2 ^21. Since the two sum is only equal to power of 2, the total possible accumulations are within [1,2,4,8,16,..,2^21].** 

1st Solution: (Two Pointers + Map)
```
class Solution {
private:
    long long comb(long long num) {
        return (long long)(num * (num - 1) / 2);
    }

public:
    int countPairs(vector<int>& deliciousness) {
        int mod = 1e9 + 7;
        map<int, int> m;
        for(auto& d : deliciousness) {
            ++m[d];
        }
        int res = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i <= 21; ++i) {
            int power = (1 << i);
            for(auto e : m) {
                if(power - e.first == e.first) {
                    res += comb(m[e.first]) % mod;
                }
            }
            auto l = m.begin();
            auto r = prev(m.end());
            while(l != r) {
                if((l->first + r->first) == power) {
                    res += l->second * r->second;
                    l = next(l);
                }
                else if(l->first + r->first < power) {
                    l = next(l);
                }
                else {
                    r = prev(r);
                }
            }
            res = (res % mod + mod) % mod;
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```
step1: save each value with the count into a map which can maintain sorted keys.
step2: for a specific value of power of 2, apply two points to find how many pairs can be found out. Note: Input: deliciousness = [1,1,1,3,3,3,7], if power of 2 is equal to 2, the good meal (1,1) has 3 ways which is 3!/2. For the good meal (1, 3) has 9 ways which 3 * 3 from key = 1 and key = 3
step3: this method would have to use long int or long long int to save the result and then modulo 10e9 + 7 

Time Complexity O(n*k)
Space Complexity O(n)

2nd Solution: (Unordered_Set)
```
class Solution {
private:
    long long comb(long long num) {
        return (long long)(num * (num - 1) / 2);
    }

public:
    int countPairs(vector<int>& deliciousness) {
        int mod = 1e9 + 7;
        map<int, int> m;
        for(auto& d : deliciousness) {
            ++m[d];
        }
        long long res = 0;
        for(int i = 0; i <= 21; ++i) {
            int power = (1 << i);
            unordered_set<int> us;
            for(auto e : m) {
                if(us.find(e.first) == us.end() && m.find(power - e.first) != m.end()) {
                    if(e.first == power - e.first) {
                        res += comb(m[e.first]);
                    }
                    else {
                        res += e.second * m[power - e.first];
                    }
                    us.insert(e.first);
                    us.insert(power - e.first);
                }
                res %= mod;
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
};
```

The idea is similiar to two pointers but it uses an unordered_set for each iteraiton for avoiding duplicating caculation.
