solutions.content:
Assume L/M/R are sums of three subarrarys:
* `j` is the start index of the right subarray
* `i1` is the maximum start index of the middle subarray that NOT qualifies `M <= R` when `j` is fixed
* `i2` is the maximum start index of the middle subarray that qualifies `L <= M` when `j` is fixed

We can fix right subarray each time, and use **binary search** to find `i1` and `i2`. But we also notice that for adjacent `j`s, there is a correlation between their corresponding `i1`s and `i2`s, so we can do it better.

Detailed explanation:
* pre-calculate prefix sum (can be eliminated to further improve space complexity)
* move `j` from right to left
* when `j` moves left one element, `R` will increase and `M` will decrease
* thus, both `i1` and `i2` has to move to the left side to meet the above requirements
* so we move `i1` and `i2` to the left until the above requirements are met, then add `i2 - i1` to the res

time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(n), can be optimized to O(1) by memorizing `prefix[i1]`, `prefix[i2]`, `prefix[j]`

```
class Solution {
  public int waysToSplit(int[] nums) {
    final int N = nums.length;
    int[] prefix = new int[N + 1];
    for (int i = 0; i < N; i++) {
      prefix[i + 1] = prefix[i] + nums[i];
    }
    long res = 0;
    int i1 = N - 2;
    int i2 = N - 2;
    for (int j = N - 1; j >= 2; j--) {
      int right = prefix[N] - prefix[j];
      while (i1 > 0 && prefix[j] - prefix[i1] <= right) {
	    // M <= R
        i1--;
      }
      i2 = Math.min(i2, j - 1);
      while (i2 > 0 && prefix[i2] > prefix[j] - prefix[i2]) {
	    // L > M
        i2--;
      }
      if (i2 > i1 && i1 >= 0) {
        res += (long) (i2 - i1);
      }      
    }    
    return (int) (res % 1_000_000_007);
  }
}
```

