solutions.content:
the key point here is how can you find the right boundary between second and third array.
One way is to use binary search by target value; (O(nlgn))
The other way is use another pointer to find the cutting point, naively from i+1 to n - 2 everytime when i increases (O(n2)). However, this can be further optimized by not starting from i+1 everytime but use the previously scanned value. (O(n))

```
class Solution {
    public int waysToSplit(int[] nums) {
        int mod = (int) Math.pow(10, 9) + 7;
        int n = nums.length;
        int[] sums = new int[n+1];
        for (int i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
            sums[i] = sums[i-1] + nums[i-1];
        }

        long res = 0;
        int j = 1;
        int k = 2;
        for (int i = 0; i < n - 2; i++) {
            int left = sums[i+1];
            int target = (sums[n] - sums[i+1]) / 2;
            if (target < left) {
                break;
            }

            while (j <= i || j < n - 1 && sums[j+1] - sums[i+1] < left) {
                j++;
            }

            while (k < j || k < n - 1 && sums[k+1] - sums[i+1] <= sums[n] - sums[k+1]) {
                k++;
            }
            res = (res + k - j) % mod;
        }
        return (int) res;
    }
}
```

