Assuming `prefix` array has the prefix sum of the `nums`. The main condition to generate is:
```
leftSum <= midSum <= rightSum  - (i)

leftSum = prefix[i]
midSum = prefix[mid] - leftSum
rightSum = prefix[end] - prefix[mid]

2*prefix[i] <= prefix[mid] <= (prefix[end] + prefix[i])/2  - (ii)
```

Now we need to find the `lower_bound` for left part and `upper_bound` for right part in `(ii)`. That would give us the interval in which the condition `(i)` would be true. 

Here is my code:
```
class Solution {
public:
    int waysToSplit(vector<int>& nums) {
        vector<int> prefix;
        int sum = 0;
        for (int num : nums) {
            sum += num;
            prefix.push_back(sum);
        }

        int cnt = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.size() - 2; ++i) {
            auto lo = lower_bound(prefix.begin() + i + 1, prefix.end(), 
                                  2*prefix[i]);
            auto up = upper_bound(prefix.begin() + i + 1, prefix.end() - 1, 
                                  (prefix.back() + prefix[i])/2);
            if (lo < up)
                cnt = (cnt + up - lo) % mod;
        }

        return cnt;
    }

private:
    const int mod = 1e9 + 7;
};
```

Note: `prefix.end()-1` for the `upper_bound` is to not search till the end of the `prefix` array since then we won't have a 3-way split that way.

