solutions.content:
For an index i, we divide right array from i->n and find the limits of mid array from 0->i
The left and right limits are the min value we can give to mid array and max value we can give to 
mid array. Can be done using two pointers. One for the left limit and one for right limit.
If our mid exceeds right, then we need to increase our max limit pointer forward so that left array
is given some value from mid. Now till the left array does not exceed mid array value we increase our
min limit pointer. 
The answer for each index is max of min limit - max limit  and 0.
```
typedef long long ll;
class Solution {
public:
    int waysToSplit(vector<int>& nums) {
        ll M = 1e9+7;
        int n = nums.size();
        ll total = accumulate(nums.begin(), nums.end(), 0);
        // 0->left limit, left limit -> right limit, left limit -> i, right limit -> i
        ll left1 = nums[0], left2 = nums[0], mid1 = 0, mid2 = 0;
        int low = 0, high = 0;
        ll ans = 0;
        for(int i=1; i<n-1; i++){
            mid1 += nums[i];
            mid2 += nums[i];
            while(mid1 > (total-mid1-left1) && low < i){
                left1 += nums[++low];
                mid1 -= nums[low];
            }
            while(left2 <= mid2 && high < i){
                left2 += nums[++high];
                mid2 -= nums[high];
            }
            ans += max<ll>(high-low,0);
            ans %= M;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

